Yes, it was implemented with version 2.1.12's updating scripts - specifically around line 760 in /update/off_schedule_update.php - with this code:

```
if (!check_update("archiveScoresheet", $prefix."archive")) {

	$updateSQL = sprintf("ALTER TABLE `%s` CHANGE `archiveBrewingTableName` `archiveScoresheet` CHAR(1) CHARACTER SET utf8mb4 COLLATE utf8mb4_unicode_ci NULL DEFAULT NULL;",$prefix."archive");
	mysqli_select_db($connection,$database);
	mysqli_real_escape_string($connection,$updateSQL);
	$result = mysqli_query($connection,$updateSQL);

	// Set all to 'J'
	$updateSQL = sprintf("UPDATE `%s` SET archiveScoresheet='J';",$prefix."archive");
	mysqli_select_db($connection,$database);
	mysqli_real_escape_string($connection,$updateSQL);
	$result = mysqli_query($connection,$updateSQL);

}
```

You can force an update by changing the FORCE_UPDATE constant in the paths.php script to TRUE, uploading to your installation, and accessing index.php a single time. This should make the necessary DB changes.

After that, change the var back to FALSE and re-upload.

Hi @grmelacz, first, thank you for your translation efforts!

Since no other languages besides US English have been incorporated into the BCOE&M core as of the current release (2.1.12), you'll need to comment out the both of the _include_ lines in the /lang/language.lang.php file, like this:
```
//include (LANG.$_SESSION['prefsLanguageFolder'].DIRECTORY_SEPARATOR.$_SESSION['prefsLanguage'].'.lang.php');
//include (LANG.$_SESSION['prefsLanguageFolder'].DIRECTORY_SEPARATOR.$_SESSION['prefsLanguage'].'_admin.lang.php');
```

Then, compose two new include statements that direct the program to your newly created directory and file. 

If you followed the establish folder-file convention, you created a sub-directory in the /lang/ directory named _cs_ - the accepted ISO 639 two-letter abbreviation for Czech. Your translation file should be within that folder and named thus `cs-XX.lang.php` (replace the XX with the regional subtag). Most likely, this is CZ (all capitals).

So, your include code would look like this:
```
include (LANG.'cs'.DIRECTORY_SEPARATOR.'cs-CZ.lang.php');
include (LANG.'cs'.DIRECTORY_SEPARATOR.'cs-CZ_admin.lang.php');
```

Re-upload the language.lang.php file to the /lang/ directory and you should be in business.

In the next version, this process will be automatic based upon a site preference.

One request: when you're done with your translation efforts, **please post the file** here so it can be incorporated into a future release (you'll need to post a .txt or .zip file). Or, post a link to a [gist here on GitHub](https://help.github.com/articles/creating-gists/).

@dmofot @geoffhumphrey This might be useful and is working on my nginx configuration.  You might like to add this to the documentation as an example.

```
server {
    listen 80;

    root /usr/share/nginx/sites/example.com/web/content;
    index index.php index.html index.htm;

    server_name example.com www.example.com;

    rewrite ^/$ /index.php break;
    rewrite ^/([A-Za-z0-9-]+)?$ /index.php?section=$1 break;
    rewrite ^/([A-Za-z0-9-]+)/([A-Za-z0-9-]+)/?$ /index.php?section=$1&go=$2 break;
    rewrite ^/([A-Za-z0-9-]+)/([A-Za-z0-9-]+)/([A-Za-z0-9-]+)/?$ /index.php?section=$1&go=$2&action=$3 break;
    rewrite ^/([A-Za-z0-9-]+)/([A-Za-z0-9-]+)/([A-Za-z0-9-]+)/([A-Za-z0-9-]+)/?$ /index.php?section=$1&go=$2&action=$3&id=$4 break;

    location / {
        try_files $uri $uri/ /index.php?$args;
    }

    location ~ \.php$ {
        try_files $uri =404;
        fastcgi_split_path_info ^(.+\.php)(/.+)$;
        fastcgi_pass unix:/var/run/php-fpm.sock;
        fastcgi_index index.php;
        fastcgi_param SCRIPT_FILENAME $document_root$fastcgi_script_name;
        include fastcgi_params;
    }
}
```
